# {{.Name}} ({{.Type}})

Manages the CloudPilot AI Workload Autoscaler on a Kubernetes cluster. This resource installs the autoscaler components, configures recommendation policies, and sets up autoscaling policies for workload right-sizing.

## Example Usage

{{ tffile "examples/resources/cloudpilotai_workload_autoscaler/resource.tf" }}

### Advanced Workload Autoscaler Config

```terraform
enable_new_workloads_proactive_update          = false
limiter_quota_per_window                      = 5
limiter_burst                                 = 10
limiter_window_seconds                        = 30
enable_preempted_pod_gc                       = true
preempted_pod_gc_ttl                          = "30m"
enable_initial_optimization_data_window_check = true

recommendation_policies = [
  {
    name                             = "java"
    history_window_cpu               = "24h"
    history_window_memory            = "48h"
    evaluation_period                = "1m"
    jvm_heap_buffer                  = "300Mi"
    jvm_min_heap_xms_ratio_of_memory = "0.25"
    jvm_recent_non_heap_window       = "2h"
    jvm_heap_used_percentile         = 20
  }
]

autoscaling_policies = [
  {
    name                         = "default-ap"
    recommendation_policy_name   = "java"
    disable_runtime_optimization = false
    in_place_fallback_reason_policies = {
      JVMHeapDrift = "hold"
    }
    target_refs = [
      {
        api_version = "apps/v1"
        kind        = "Deployment"
        label_selector = {
          match_labels = { app = "api" }
          match_expressions = [
            { key = "tier", operator = "In", values = ["backend"] }
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
]
```

An explicitly configured `kubeconfig` must contain working auth for the target cluster. When `kubeconfig` is omitted, the provider generates an execution-local path without storing it in Terraform state. GKE access uses `gcp_project_id` and `gcp_cluster_location` when set, then falls back to cluster metadata and local gcloud credentials. EKS access uses `aws_profile`, `aws_assume_role`, or the ambient AWS credential chain.

{{ .SchemaMarkdown | trimspace }}

## Upgrading from Generated Kubeconfig State

Older provider versions could store an automatically generated kubeconfig path in this resource. If `kubeconfig` is not configured, the first plan with the fixed provider will change that legacy value to `null`. Apply the in-place update; no state edit, re-import, or replacement is required. EKS users who omit `kubeconfig` should configure `aws_profile` and/or `aws_assume_role` when ambient AWS credentials are not sufficient.

When upgrading legacy Workload Autoscaler state that requires non-ambient AWS credentials or non-default GCP project/location settings, run one normal apply with this resource still enabled before destroying it or setting its module count to zero. Terraform does not send resource configuration to providers for a legacy delete, so the upgrade apply is what records the new access fields and removes the stale path.

## Import

Import only requires a valid CloudPilot AI API key — no AWS credentials or kubeconfig needed. All configuration (including recommendation and autoscaling policies) is fetched from the CloudPilot AI API.

{{ codefile "shell" "examples/resources/cloudpilotai_workload_autoscaler/import.sh" }}

After importing, the resource state will contain all recommendation and autoscaling policies fetched from the server. You can then manage them via `terraform apply`.

~> **Note:** Create, update, and delete operations require live cluster access. Configure `kubeconfig`, or provide the local GCP/AWS credentials needed for execution-local kubeconfig generation. EKS assume-role users should also configure `aws_profile` and/or `aws_assume_role` on this resource.
